KnobMixer
Free per-app volume control for keyboard knobs & hotkeys — Windows
Control the volume of individual apps independently using your keyboard knobs or any hotkeys you choose. Turn one knob for your game, another for Discord, another for your browser — all at the same time.
---
Download
👉 Download KnobMixer
Requires: Windows 10 or 11 (64-bit)
---
How to set it up
Step 1 — Program your keyboard (skip if your knob can't be remapped)
Open your keyboard's software and set your knob keys to these recommended keys:
Knob left → F13 (Vol-)
Knob right → F14 (Vol+)
Knob click → F15 (Mute)
Step 2 — Choose your mode in KnobMixer
Multiple Knobs — each group has its own hotkeys. Best if you have multiple knobs
1-Knob mode — one knob controls volume for all groups, press a key to switch between groups
Step 3 — Set your hotkeys
In KnobMixer, assign the hotkeys you set in Step 1 to your groups. Each group controls a set of apps you choose. In 1-Knob mode, the shared keys are set above the groups on the main window.
Step 4 — Add your apps
Click Edit on each group and add the apps you want it to control (e.g. Spotify, Discord, your game). When an app is open, it appears in the list for easy adding.
---
Hardware knob that can't be remapped? (e.g. AULAF75)
Enable Hardware Knob in Settings → 1-Knob Mode. KnobMixer will intercept the system volume keys and redirect them to control your active group instead — system volume stays untouched.
---
No knob? No problem.
KnobMixer works with any hotkey combination — keyboard shortcuts, mouse buttons, or stream deck keys.
---
Features
Per-app volume groups — assign any app to a group
Master Volume group — control your entire PC volume
Mic toggle with floating icon
Volume popup overlay —
Hardware knob support for fixed-key keyboards
Starts with Windows, lives in the system tray
Lightweight — ~0% CPU at idle, ~40MB RAM
Free. No ads. No login. No background services.
